\begin_layout Subsection
Not done in good faith
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Can science be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

objective
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

? Can we 
\series bold
trust
\series default
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

truths
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that economists have established? 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

If I know that you know that...
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Science cannot be objective, by definition.
 When economists pretend to be very scientific, it is worth asking: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

do they have something to gain from it? How many economists who 
\series bold
believe
\series default
 in the free market, also 
\series bold
benefit
\series default
 from it? Example with Michel Faucault: society decides what is normal,
 as there is no such thing as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

perfect objectivity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the example with traffic: everyone wants to leave just a minute
 before the traffic, but that's impossible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Shouldn't we be more suspicious? Probably, yes.
 We can try to be more objective, but it is a 
\series bold
direction
\series default
, not a 
\series bold
place
\series default
.
 There is a distinction between 
\series bold
positive
\series default
 (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

is
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) social science and 
\series bold
normative 
\series default
(
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ought
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 In physics, normative science is considered science fiction, but in social
 science it makes sense.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How do we judge theories? Positive theories can be judged by how close to
 reality they are.
 A good normative theory is one that describes the society we 
\series bold
want
\series default
 to be (it doesn't have to describe the reality as it currently is).
 Normative is 
\series bold
the second-order positive
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to distinguish 
\series bold
positive
\series default
 from 
\series bold
normative
\series default
 - the theories might never be totally objective (positive), but it doesn't
