\begin_layout Subsection
Marginal Utility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It took humanity quite a long to get to these concepts.
 Adam Smith's claim was that price and utility have nothing in common.
 According to him, the price is determined solely by the cost of production.
 Even Richardo at 1870 believed in that.
 Examples: water (cannot live without it, costs nothing) vs.
 diamonds (very expensive, can live without them).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was only around ~1870s that 4 independent people (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the marginalist revolution
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 figured out the notion of 
\series bold
marginal
\series default
 utility (don't look at the overall utility, but at the derivative).
 The reason that water costs nothing is that extra glass of water doesn't
 give any utility (you already have enough).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a normative interpretation to utility function: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

would you 
\series bold
like
\series default
