\begin_layout Section
Consumer Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Basic Concepts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A basic distinction msut be made between what we 
\series bold
can
\series default
 do and what we 
\series bold
want
\series default
 to do (they are logically independent).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Aesop's fox said that he didn't want the grapes he couldn't get.
 Marx: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I refuse to join any club that whould haהe me as a member
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Both cases have the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rationality sin
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: they mix what they want with what they can do.
 From a psychological point of view, the fox is healthier (at least he doesn't
 want something he is unable to get).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We 
\series bold
can
\series default
 choose particular quantities of goods, depending on their price and the
 
\series bold
budget constraint
\series default
.
 If prices are 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{x},p_{y}$
\end_inset

 and the income is 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, the constraint is given by: 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{x}x+p_{y}y\leq I$
\end_inset

.
 This is the simplest model (more complicated cases might include discounting,
 discrete points, etc).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The objective function is 
\series bold
maximization of utility
\series default
, subject to the budget constaint.
 Thus, the question is: which points in the feasible set have the highest
 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 values?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Indifference Curves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Instead of describing the actual level of the utility function (it might
 not be possible, and not needed at all, as it is only an ordinal) - we
 only describe bundles which have the same utility level, by connecting
 points with equal utlity.
 Points along an IC are equally desirable, while higher ICs are more desirable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Optimization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal is to match the ICs with the feasible set, to find the highest
 affordable IC.
 It is found by equality of slopes (IC shall be 
\series bold
tangent
\series default
 to the feasible set), using the 
\series bold
marginality condition
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Marginality Condifion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The budget line must be tangent to the IC, otherwise there would be a contradict
ion (i.e a higher IC is affordable).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The slope of the budget constraint:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{x}x+p_{y}y=I\Rightarrow\frac{b}{a}=\frac{p_{x}}{p_{y}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

long
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 way to calculate it: how many 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 need to be given up to gain extra 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and remain on the same line:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{x}(x+a)+p_{y}(y-b)=I
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The indifference curve is not linear, thus its slope calculation is more
 subtle.
 What matters here is the partial derivatives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(x,y)=c
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(x+a,y-b)=c\Rightarrow U_{x}a-U_{y}b\cong0\Rightarrow\frac{b}{a}\cong\frac{U_{x}}{U_{y}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(x+a,y-b)=U(x,y)+aU_{x}-bU_{y}+c(a,b)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea above is the same as with approximation of a single-argument function
 (Calculus I).
 In summary, the point of equality of slopes is to be found (algebraically),
 which is the point where functions are tangent (on terms of geometry):
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{U_{x}}{U_{y}}=\frac{p_{x}}{p_{y}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That's the point of intersection between the 
\series bold
market
\series default
 (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

what I can
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) and 
\series bold
personal preferences
\series default
 (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

what I want
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rearranging the terms leads to another condition:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{U_{x}}{p_{x}}=\frac{U_{y}}{p_{y}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In both sides, psychology and economics are mixed (psychology in the numerator,
 economics in the denominator).
\end_layout

